I. 1. In every proceeding in which there is a dispute as to
3
4
the custody of a minor child, a determination by the court that
4
5
child abuse, domestic violence, stalking, or harassment has occurred
5
6
raises a rebuttable presumption that sole custody, joint legal or
6
7
physical custody, or any shared parenting plan with the perpetrator
7
8
of child abuse, domestic violence, harassing, or stalking behavior
8
9
is detrimental and not in the best interest of the child, and it is
9
10
in the best interest of the child to reside with the parent who is
10
11
not a perpetrator of child abuse, domestic violence, harassing, or
11
12
stalking behavior. Further, in proceedings stated above, where a
12
13
parent is required to register pursuant to the Sex Offenders
13
14
Registration Act, the Mary Rippy Violent Crime Offenders
14
15
Registration Act, or a similar registration in another state, there
15
16
shall be a rebuttable presumption that sole custody, joint legal or
16
17
physical custody, or any shared parenting plan with the parent
17
18
subject to any of the above acts is detrimental and not in the best
18
19
interest of the child and it is in the best interest of the child to
19
20
reside with the parent who is not subject to any of the above acts.
20
21
2. For the purposes of this subsection:
21
22
a. “child abuse” shall have the same meaning as “abuse”
